english:
  title: 'Driving Out the Poetry Demon: A Missive to Expel Poverty'
  author: Lee Gyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Consider how accumulated earth rises into hills, how collected water deepens into wells—these and the trees, stones, houses, and walls are all lifeless things between heaven and earth. Yet when spirits attach to them and display their strange and spectral nature, people despise and fear them, curse and drive them away. In extreme cases, they level the hills, plug the wells, fell the trees, shatter the stones, demolish the houses, and tear down the walls. So too with people. In the beginning, humans were simple and unadorned, pure and upright. But once they succumb to poetry's sorcery, their words grow strange, their phrases dance, things become confused, and people are bewildered. This springs from no other cause than the work of this demon. Therefore I dare enumerate its crimes and banish it thus:

    "When people first came into this world, they possessed primal simplicity—unadorned and undecorated as flowers not yet in bloom, their clarity obscured as if their senses had never been opened. Who fashioned that door? Who gave that key? And the demon came bursting in, presuming to lodge itself here, dazzling the world and bewildering mankind, adorning them with beauty, spinning illusions and conjuring wonders—making them stumble and dance in throngs. Some it made writhe with softened bones, others it startled with wind-swept chaos. The world, never as robust as you, why do you make it leap and bound? Mankind, never possessing such craft, why do you make them carve and polish so? This is your first crime.

    "Earth cherishes stillness; heaven cannot be named. The mysteries of creation and divinity are vast and obscure, their mechanisms sealed tight. Yet you, thinking nothing, spy upon the divine and expose its secrets with shameless boldness. You thrust at the moon until it aches; you pierce heaven until it trembles. The spirits grow displeased, the heavens grow angry. Through you, human life becomes harsh and bitter. This is your second crime.

    "The brilliance of clouds and sunset, the purity of moon and dew, the strangeness of insects and fish, the peculiarity of birds and beasts—the flowers and plants that sprout and bloom with ten thousand forms adorning heaven and earth—you seize these without shame, leaving nothing unconsumed, singing of each thing as you perceive it, gathering them without end. Your shameless greed offends heaven and earth. This is your third crime.

    "Meeting an enemy, one attacks directly—what need for cannons or ramparts? For those you favor, you make splendid without court robes; for those you despise, you wound without blades. What axe do you wield to be so reckless with war? What authority do you claim to wield rewards and punishments at will? You are no court official, yet you meddle in state affairs. You are no fool, yet you mock all creation. Strutting about with empty boasts, standing stiff with false superiority—who would not envy you? Who would not hate you? This is your fourth crime.

    "When you attach to a person, it is like plague and pestilence—the body grows filthy, the hair tangled, the beard falls and the face becomes bloated. You torment their voice, furrow their brow, drain their spirit, and waste their heart. You are the herald of calamity and the thief of peace. This is your fifth crime.

    "Bearing these five crimes, how do you dare to possess mankind? You clung to Chen Si and made him despise his brother—was the bean's cry in the cauldron not the fault of the pod? You possessed Li Bai and drove him mad—he grasped for the moon and fell into waters, leaving only an endless river. You seized Du Fu and beset him with hardship—wandering desolate in exile, he died in Leiyang, and who would mourn him? You gripped Li He and filled him with phantasms and strangeness—his talent never met the world, and an early death was his portion. You inhabited Meng De and made him revile the powerful—his arrogance could not sustain him, and at last he stumbled and could not rise. You moved Liu Zihou to stir up calamity—exiled to Liuzhou, he never returned, and who would weep for him? Alas, O demon! Why have you led so many astray, generation after generation? And now you have possessed me! Since you came, all my affairs have grown crooked. I become muddled and forget, dull and foolish, mute and deaf. My form is bound, my traces confined. I know not hunger or thirst pressing upon my body, feel not the cold and heat invading my skin. My servants grow idle yet I do not scold them; my slaves grow stubborn yet I do not govern them. The gardens wither yet I do not tend them; the house crumbles yet I do not repair it. When poverty's ghost arrives, that too is you who called it! I grow arrogant before the noble, contemptuous of the wealthy, wanton and disrespectful in all things. My words lack courtesy, my face shows no modesty. A glimpse of wine sets me astray, and when wine arrives I grow coarse and crude. This too is your doing, not mine! Like curs barking at phantoms, you gather crowds to echo your madness. I detest you, curse you, drive you away! If you do not flee swiftly, I shall seek you out and punish you!"

    That night, weary, I lay down to sleep. From my pillow came a sound of rustling, and there appeared a figure in bright robes, shimmering with light, who spoke to me thus:

    "Harsh are your words of reproach! Severe your words of rejection! Why do you hate me so? Though I am but a minor demon, heaven itself knows of me. When you first came into this world, heaven sent me to follow you. When you were an infant, naked and helpless, I hid within your home and never left. When you were a boy with unbound hair, I peeped about quietly. When you became a man with your hair bound up, I followed closely behind. I gave you courage and vigor, taught you the art of rhetoric to make your writing beautiful. At the examination grounds, year after year I made you succeed in competing in the literary arts, astounding heaven and earth, spreading your fame to the four directions, making noble and illustrious persons look up to you. Was my aid to you shallow? Was heaven's blessing to you not measureless? That which flows from the mouth, the bearing of the body, attraction to pleasure, indulgence in wine—these each have their own masters and are not my domain. Why then did you not exercise caution, acting mad and foolish? This failure is yours alone, not my fault."

    At this, the recluse—finding today right and yesterday wrong, shrinking back in embarrassment, bowing low—welcomed the demon as his teacher.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 陳思 (Chen Si) refers to Cao Zhi (曹植), the third-century poet and prince. The reference to beans crying in a cauldron alludes to his famous poem "豆蕖相煎" (Beans and Cattail), a political allegory about fraternal conflict.
  - key: ''
    value: 李白 (Li Bai) famously drowned attempting to embrace the moon's reflection, according to legend—here rendered as his attempted capture of the moon.
  - key: ''
    value: 杜甫 (Du Fu) endured exile and hardship, dying in Leiyang while traveling.
  - key: ''
    value: 李賀 (Li He) was a brilliant Tang poet whose avant-garde style was considered strange by his contemporaries; he died at age 27.
  - key: ''
    value: The poem employs the traditional Korean literary device of the demon's self-defense, ultimately showing the poet's acceptance of poetry as inseparable from human nature—a witty reversal of the initial condemnation.
